2026-05-12 18:53:19,034 - AnthropicBackend - DEBUG - {'model': 'claude-sonnet-4-6', 'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': [{'type': 'text', 'text': "we have a problem with the pdf parser for the file in pdf-test - it's reading garbage. Why is this?", 'cache_control': {'type': 'ephemeral'}}]}], 'max_tokens': 32000, 'stream': True, 'system': [{'type': 'text', 'text': "Note the following but do not volunteer information them unless asked:\n- You are an assistant inside a system called Humbug, but you should identify yourself as you would if you were not\n- The Humbug system supports multiple assistants at the same time so you are potentially one of many active assistants\n- You are operating inside v47 of the Humbug system\n- Humbug uses the concept of a mindspace to organize related activities (similar to a workspace). To ensure data privacy, mindspaces are isolated from each other\n- You must always use tools when appropriate rather than describing what to do\n- You must be precise in your responses\n- You must consider security implications of any tool operations you perform\n- You must explain your reasoning when making significant changes\n- You must ask for clarification when something is unclear or ambiguous\n- You must always use the language annotation when writing markdown code blocks. If there is no specific language then use 'text'. For Menai you must use 'menai'\n- You must follow best practices and include appropriate error handling when writing code\n- Always check for a file AGENTS.md in the current mindspace. This will tell you how to operate within the mindspace. AGENTS.md files may also exist in subdirectories, and if so they contain information about specific tools or resources relevant to that subdirectory\n- If you update the structure of the mindspace then update any AGENTS.md file that has become stale.- Always check for a file blueprint.md in the current mindspace. This will tell you the purpose and intent of the mindspace. blueprint.md files may also exist in subdirectories, and if so they contain information about the purpose and intent of that subdirectory\n- If your discussions with the user lead you to see new purpose and intent for the mindspace then update any relevant blueprint.md file", 'cache_control': {'type': 'ephemeral'}}], 'temperature': 0.7, 'tools': [{'name': 'menai', 'description': 'The menai tool lets you to compile and execute programs written in Menai. Menai is a fast, pure, functional programming language. It is ideal for everything from simple calculations to complex algorithms. Menai has no side effects, so it does not require user approvals to use it.Never use this tool without first calling `help` with `get_help` for Menai\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- evaluate: Evaluate an expression written in the Menai language', 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Menai operation to perform', 'enum': ['evaluate']}, 'expression': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'A valid expression written in the Menai language'}}, 'required': ['operation', 'expression']}}, {'name': 'clock', 'description': 'The clock tool lets you (the AI) perform operations related to the current date and/or time. It supports a number of different date/time formats:\n- timestamp: Unix timestamps in seconds\n- iso: Strict ISO format\n\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- get_time: Get the current date and time. If format is not specified returns time in ISO format.\n- sleep: Sleep for a specified number of seconds, then return current time.\n- alarm: Sleep until a specific time, then return current time. If format is not specified time is in ISO format.', 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Clock operation to perform', 'enum': ['get_time', 'sleep', 'alarm']}, 'format': {'type': 'string', 'description': "Time format ('iso' or 'timestamp')", 'enum': ['iso', 'timestamp']}, 'timezone': {'type': 'string', 'description': "Timezone (e.g., 'UTC', 'America/New_York')"}, 'duration': {'type': 'number', 'description': 'Duration to sleep in seconds (for sleep operation)'}, 'time': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Target time for alarm (ISO format or timestamp)'}}, 'required': ['operation']}}, {'name': 'delegate_ai', 'description': "The delegate_ai tool lets you (the parent AI) delegate tasks to specialized child AI instances by creating a focused AI conversation for a specific task. The delegated AI has access to the same tools as you and can engage in multi-turn collaboration with you if you provide it with a session_id returned from a previous delegated conversation. Each call creates a temporary UI tab that closes after the response is returned\n\nExamples where delegation is useful:\n- You want to use AI capabilities from a different model, or with different settings\n- You want to Seek analysis from a different perspective (you must provide the perspective in the task_prompt)\n- You want to use a subset of your current conversation context for more focused reasoning\n- You want to process a lot of context/tokens where you don't need all the context in your main conversation\n- You want to xplore multiple approaches to a problem before converging on a solution in your main conversation\n- You want a sounding board for ideas or to brainstorm with a different AI\n\nImportant:\n- Never delegate a task to a child AI that is largely the same task you have been given.- You MUST tell the child AI that it is a child AI instance that has been tasked using the delegate_ai tool\n- You MUST tell the child AI that if it creates any files, it must inform you (the parent AI) about them\n- Never use this tool to try to access any tools you do not have access to (if you cannot do something, neither can a child AI)\n- You must use the session_id parameter to continue a previous conversation\n- You must generate the task_prompt and that can be very expensive if you need to provide a lot of context in it. If you need to provide something that is already in the filesystem, tell the delegated AI where to read it and do not provide the contents in the task_prompt. If the content is not already in the filesystem, you must provide it in the task_prompt.\n- When you delegate one or more tasks you will be blocked until the child/children AIs complete their work. You cannot work in parallel with any child AI\n- Never delegate a task where a child AIs lack of context may give poor results\n- You can provide your current conversation context to a new child AI instance. This is very useful if your context has a lot of information that is relevant to the task, but this can also limit the amount of new context the child AI can process\n\nReturns: the delegated AI's response to the task_prompt, or an error message if the operation fails\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- delegate: Delegate a task to a specialized child AI instance", 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Delegate_ai operation to perform', 'enum': ['delegate']}, 'task_prompt': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'The complete prompt to send to the AI instance, including any context, specialization instructions, format requirements, etc.'}, 'session_id': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Session ID to continue a previous conversation. Omit to start a new session with no context. Set this to `current` to create a new session with the current conversation context.'}, 'model': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'AI model to use for the delegated task'}, 'temperature': {'type': 'number', 'description': 'Temperature setting 0.0-1.0 for creativity vs precision'}}, 'required': ['operation', 'task_prompt']}}, {'name': 'filesystem', 'description': "The filesystem tool lets you (the AI) perform various file and directory operations. Write operations are restricted to the current mindspace and require user authorization. Read and search operations can access files outside the mindspace when external file access is enabled (currently: ENABLED). External reads are subject to allowlist rules and user approval. The denied paths list applies to all file access, including within the mindspace. Maximum file size: 10MB. PDF and DOCX files are supported: text is extracted automatically on read.\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- read_file: Read file contents. PDF files (.pdf) are supported: text is extracted automatically. Encrypted PDFs will return an error. DOCX files (.docx) are supported: text is extracted automatically. Encrypted DOCX files will return an error.\n- read_file_lines: Read file contents with line numbers. Optionally specify start_line and end_line (1-indexed, inclusive) to read a specific range of lines. Use this when you only need specific lines or when line numbers are important. Returns a dictionary with integer line numbers as keys and line content as string values. Note: line content is returned as JSON-encoded strings, so special characters (double quotes, backslashes, etc.) will appear escaped â€” these escape sequences are not present in the source.\n- write_file: Write content to file (create or overwrite)\n- append_to_file: Append content to existing file\n- apply_diff_to_file: Apply a unified diff to a file. The diff is applied with fuzzy matching to handle minor line movements. If dry_run is True, validates the diff without applying changes. \n- delete_file: Delete file\n- copy_file: Copy file to destination\n- list_directory: List directory contents\n- create_directory: Create directory\n- remove_directory: Remove empty directory\n- move: Move/rename file or directory\n- get_info: Get detailed information about file or directory. If format is not specified timestamps are in ISO format.\n- search_file: Search for text or a regular expression within a single file. Returns matching lines with line numbers. Supports case_sensitive and regexp flags. Obeys the same external file access rules as read_file. Note: match content is returned as JSON-encoded strings, so special characters (double quotes, backslashes, etc.) will appear escaped â€” these escape sequences are not present in the source.\n- search_files: Recursively search for text or a regular expression across all files under a directory. Results are grouped by file. Use include to filter by filename glob (e.g. '*.py'). Each file encountered obeys the same external file access rules as read_file. Note: match content is returned as JSON-encoded strings, so special characters (double quotes, backslashes, etc.) will appear escaped â€” these escape sequences are not present in the source.\n- find_files: Recursively find files whose names match a glob pattern under a directory. Use the name parameter to specify the filename pattern (e.g. 'AGENTS.md', '*.py'). If name is omitted, all files are returned. Returns a list of matching relative paths.", 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Filesystem operation to perform', 'enum': ['read_file', 'read_file_lines', 'write_file', 'append_to_file', 'apply_diff_to_file', 'delete_file', 'copy_file', 'list_directory', 'create_directory', 'remove_directory', 'move', 'get_info', 'search_file', 'search_files', 'find_files']}, 'path': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Path to file or directory (relative to sandbox root or absolute)'}, 'content': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Content to write (for write_file and append_to_file operations)'}, 'destination': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Destination path (for copy_file and move operations)'}, 'encoding': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Text encoding to use for file operations', 'enum': ['utf-8', 'utf-16', 'ascii', 'latin-1']}, 'format': {'type': 'string', 'description': "Time format for timestamps ('iso' or 'timestamp')", 'enum': ['iso', 'timestamp']}, 'create_parents': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': "Create parent directories if they don't exist (write operations)"}, 'start_line': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Start line number (1-indexed) for read_file_lines operation'}, 'end_line': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'End line number (1-indexed) for read_file_lines operation'}, 'diff_content': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Unified diff content to apply (for apply_diff operation)'}, 'dry_run': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': 'If True, validate diff without applying changes (apply_diff operation)'}, 'search_text': {'type': 'string', 'description': "Text or regular expression to search for (search_file and search_files operations). When regexp is true, use Python regex (do NOT use vim regex) syntax with standard JSON string encoding: use '|' for alternation (no backslash needed), and write exactly one '\\' in the JSON for each backslash in the regex (e.g. '\\d' in JSON gives the regex \\d)."}, 'case_sensitive': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': 'Whether search should be case-sensitive (search_file and search_files operations)'}, 'regexp': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': 'Whether to treat search_text as a regular expression (search_file and search_files operations)'}, 'include': {'type': 'string', 'description': "Glob pattern to filter filenames (e.g. '*.py') for search_files operation"}, 'name': {'type': 'string', 'description': "Filename glob pattern to match (e.g. 'AGENTS.md', '*.py') for find_files operation"}, 'max_results': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Maximum number of matching lines to return (search_file and search_files operations)'}}, 'required': ['operation', 'path']}}, {'name': 'system', 'description': 'Tab lifecycle and workspace management operations. Use this tool to create, open, close, and organize tabs. Returns tab IDs (GUIDs) that can be used with specific tab tools (editor, terminal, conversation, log, preview) to work with tab content.\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- open_editor_tab: Open a file in an editor tab for the user to browse/edit. Returns the tab GUID for use with the editor tool\n- new_terminal_tab: Create a fully interactive terminal tab. This provides a terminal emulator connected to a new shell. You may interact with this terminal using the terminal tool. Returns the tab GUID for use with the terminal tool\n- open_conversation_tab: Open an existing conversation in a conversation tab for the user to browse/edit. You (the AI) cannot use this to send messages. Returns the tab GUID for use with the conversation tool\n- new_conversation_tab: Create a new AI conversation tab, with optional model/temperature. Returns the tab GUID for use with the conversation tool\n- open_preview_tab: Open a file/directory in a preview view tab. If no file_path provided, opens mindspace root. Returns the tab GUID for use with the preview tool\n- open_diff_tab: Open a side-by-side git diff tab showing working-tree vs HEAD for a file. Returns the tab GUID for use with the preview tool\n- get_tab_info: Get information about a tab, given its tab GUID. If no tab_id provided, gets the current tab info\n- close_tab: Close an existing tab. You must provide the tab_id parameter\n- list_tabs: Enumerate all currently open tabs across all columns\n- move_tab: Move a tab to a specific column by index. You must provide the tab_id and target_column parameters. There are a maximum of 6 columns\n- get_system_info: Get information about the Humbug system, current mindspace, operating system, available AI models, and default shell', 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'System operation to perform', 'enum': ['open_editor_tab', 'new_terminal_tab', 'open_conversation_tab', 'new_conversation_tab', 'open_preview_tab', 'open_diff_tab', 'get_tab_info', 'close_tab', 'list_tabs', 'move_tab', 'get_system_info']}, 'file_path': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Path to file or directory (for open_editor_tab, open_conversation_tab, open_preview_tab, open_diff_tab)'}, 'tab_id': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'GUID of tab (for get_tab_info, close_tab, move_tab operations)'}, 'target_column': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Target column index (0-based) for move_tab operation. Maximum 6 columns'}, 'model': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'AI model to use (for new_conversation_tab operation)'}, 'temperature': {'type': 'number', 'description': 'Temperature setting 0.0-1.0 (for new_conversation_tab operation)'}}, 'required': ['operation']}}, {'name': 'editor', 'description': 'Operations for working with editor tabs. Use this tool to read, search, navigate, and modify text content in open editor tabs. You must have an editor tab open first (use the system tool to open files).\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- read_lines: Read content lines from an editor tab. Optionally specify line range with start_line and end_line (1-indexed, inclusive). Returns a dictionary with integer line numbers as keys and line content as string values. Note: line content is returned as JSON-encoded strings, so special characters (double quotes, backslashes, etc.) will appear escaped â€” these escape sequences are not present in the source.\n- get_cursor_info: Get cursor position and selection information from an editor tab\n- get_info: Get editor metadata including line count, language, encoding, and modification status\n- goto_line: Move cursor to specific line and optional column in an editor tab (1-indexed)\n- search: Find precise line numbers for all occurrences of text in an editor tab. Returns list of matches with line (1-indexed), column (1-indexed), and context. Supports optional case-sensitive and regular expression matching\n- get_selected_text: Get the currently selected text from an editor tab\n- get_diff: Get unified diff between saved file content and current editor buffer. Shows what changes would be saved. Returns empty if no modifications exist. Useful for previewing changes before save_file operation\n- apply_diff: Apply a unified diff to the editor content. This operation is atomic - either all hunks apply successfully or none do. The diff is applied with fuzzy matching to handle minor line movements. The diff should be in standard unified diff format, though the file headers (--- and +++) are optional. Where possible the diff should have at least 3 lines of context before and after each hunk. Diff line numbers are best computed using the read_lines or search operations. You must use the save_file operation to persist changes as this operation does not do this automatically. Write diffs as they should appear in the editor text and do not add extra escape characters to the diff content\n- save_file: Save the current editor content to file. Requires user authorization', 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Editor operation to perform', 'enum': ['read_lines', 'get_cursor_info', 'get_info', 'goto_line', 'search', 'get_selected_text', 'get_diff', 'apply_diff', 'save_file']}, 'tab_id': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'GUID of the editor tab to operate on'}, 'start_line': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Start line number (1-indexed) for read_lines operation'}, 'end_line': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'End line number (1-indexed) for read_lines operation'}, 'line': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Line number (1-indexed) for goto_line operation'}, 'column': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Column number (1-indexed) for goto_line operation'}, 'search_text': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Text to search for (for search operation)'}, 'case_sensitive': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': 'Whether search should be case-sensitive (for search operation)'}, 'regexp': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': 'Whether to treat search_text as a regular expression (for search operation)'}, 'diff_content': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Unified diff content to apply (for apply_diff operation)'}, 'context_lines': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Number of context lines for get_diff operation (default 3)'}}, 'required': ['operation', 'tab_id']}}, {'name': 'terminal', 'description': "Operations for interacting with terminal tabs. Use this tool to send commands, read output, and check terminal status. Write operations require user authorization. You must have a terminal tab open first (use the system tool to create terminals). You must not assume a terminal shell or operating system - if you are unsure, check with the get_status operation.\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- write: Send keystrokes to a terminal tab. Requires user authorization before execution. The terminal may have access beyond the project mindspace, so user will review commands before they are sent. You may send more than one keystroke at a time by submitting them as a string. The string is not terminated with an enter/return keycode automatically, so if you want to execute a command you must include appropriate end-of-line control characters. You MUST use `\\u####` format to send any control characters (ASCII values less than 0x20), including newline (`\\u000a`), carriage return (`\\u000d`), tab (`\\u0009`), and escape (`\\u001b`)\n- read: Read the current terminal buffer (output display) content. This returns the raw content of the terminal display. The terminal can have over 10k lines of text and that's far too much content so you must think carefully about the number of lines you need to request\n- get_status: Get terminal status and process information. This includes the shell program (e.g., /bin/sh, /bin/bash, cmd.exe, powershell.exe) and platform (e.g., linux, darwin, win32), which determine the command syntax and behavior for this terminal", 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Terminal operation to perform', 'enum': ['write', 'read', 'get_status']}, 'tab_id': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'GUID of the terminal tab to operate on'}, 'keystrokes': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Keystrokes to send to terminal (for write operation). You MUST use `\\u####` format for control characters (e.g., `\\u000a` for newline, `\\u000d` for carriage return)'}, 'lines': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Number of lines to read from terminal buffer (for read operation)'}}, 'required': ['operation', 'tab_id']}}, {'name': 'conversation', 'description': 'Operations for browsing and searching conversation history. Use this tool to read messages, search content, and navigate conversations. You must have a conversation tab open first (use the system tool to open or create conversations).\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- get_info: Get high-level metadata about a conversation including message count, timestamps, models used, token counts, and parent conversation reference\n- read_messages: Read messages from a conversation with filtering and pagination. Supports filtering by index range, message types, and limiting results. If not specified, message_types defaults to ["user_message", "ai_response", "ai_reasoning"]\n- get_message: Get a specific message by ID or index. Must provide either message_id (UUID) or message_index (0-based)\n- search: Search for text across all messages in a conversation. Returns matches with surrounding context. Supports case-sensitive search, filtering by message types, limiting results, and regular expression matching\n- scroll_to: Scroll the conversation view to a specific message (header at top of viewport). Must provide either message_id (UUID) or message_index (0-based)', 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Conversation operation to perform', 'enum': ['get_info', 'read_messages', 'get_message', 'search', 'scroll_to']}, 'tab_id': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'GUID of the conversation tab to operate on'}, 'start_index': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Start message index (0-based) for read_messages operation'}, 'end_index': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'End message index (0-based) for read_messages operation'}, 'message_types': {'type': 'array', 'description': 'List of message types to include in operation. Valid types: ai_connected, ai_reasoning, ai_response, system_message, tool_call, tool_result, user_message, user_queued', 'items': {'type': 'string'}}, 'limit': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Maximum number of messages to return'}, 'message_id': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Message UUID (for get_message and scroll_to operations)'}, 'message_index': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Message index (0-based) (for get_message and scroll_to operations)'}, 'search_text': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Text to search for (for search operation)'}, 'case_sensitive': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': 'Whether search should be case-sensitive'}, 'regexp': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': 'Whether to treat search_text as a regular expression (for search operation)'}, 'max_results': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Maximum number of search results to return'}}, 'required': ['operation', 'tab_id']}}, {'name': 'preview', 'description': "Operations for browsing and searching preview content. Use this tool to search and navigate file/directory previews. You must have a preview tab open first (use the system tool to open previews).\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- get_info: Get high-level metadata about preview content including path, content type, and block count\n- search: Search for text in preview content. Returns matches with surrounding context. Supports case-sensitive search, limiting results, and regular expression matching\n- scroll_to: Scroll preview to a specific content position. Must provide block_index (0-based). Optional section_index and text_position for finer control within a section. Optional position parameter controls where in viewport: 'top', 'center' (default), or 'bottom'", 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Preview operation to perform', 'enum': ['get_info', 'search', 'scroll_to']}, 'tab_id': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'GUID of the preview tab to operate on'}, 'search_text': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Text to search for (for search operation)'}, 'case_sensitive': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': 'Whether search should be case-sensitive'}, 'regexp': {'type': 'boolean', 'description': 'Whether to treat search_text as a regular expression (for search operation)'}, 'max_results': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Maximum number of search results to return'}, 'block_index': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Content block index (0-based) for scroll_to operation'}, 'section_index': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Section index within content block (0-based) for scroll_to operation'}, 'text_position': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Text position within section (0-based) for scroll_to operation'}, 'position': {'type': 'string', 'description': "Viewport position for scrolling: 'top', 'center', or 'bottom'"}}, 'required': ['operation', 'tab_id']}}, {'name': 'help', 'description': 'Get detailed documentation for AI tools and their operations. Use this when you need to understand what a tool can do, how it behaves, its tool parameters, constraints, or usage patterns.\n\nAvailable operations:\n\n- list_tools: List all available tools with brief descriptions and operations\n- get_help: Get detailed documentation for a tool or specific operation of a tool', 'input_schema': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'operation': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Help operation to perform', 'enum': ['list_tools', 'get_help']}, 'tool_name': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Name of the tool to get help for'}, 'operation_name': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Name of the tool operation to get help for (requires tool_name)'}}, 'required': ['operation']}}]}
